		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Bell's theorem</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<p><b>Bell's theorem</b> is a theorem that shows that the predictions of <a href="/wiki/Quantum_mechanics" title="Quantum mechanics">quantum mechanics</a> (QM) are counter intuitive, touching upon several fundamental philosophical issues related to modern physics. It is the most famous legacy of the late <a href="/wiki/Physicist" title="Physicist">physicist</a> <a href="/wiki/John_Stewart_Bell" title="John Stewart Bell">John S. Bell</a>. Bell's theorem is a <a href="/wiki/No-go_theorem" title="No-go theorem">no-go theorem</a>, loosely stating that:</p>
<table style="margin:auto; border-collapse:collapse; border-style:none; background-color:transparent;" class="cquote">
<tr>
<td width="20" valign="top" style="color:#B2B7F2;font-size:35px;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-weight:bold;text-align:left;padding:10px 10px;">“</td>
<td valign="top" style="padding:4px 10px;">No physical theory of <a href="/wiki/Local_hidden_variable_theory" title="Local hidden variable theory">local hidden variables</a> can ever reproduce all of the predictions of quantum mechanics.</td>
<td width="20" valign="bottom" style="color:#B2B7F2;font-size:36px;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-weight:bold;text-align:right;padding:10px 10px;">”</td>
</tr>
</table>
<table id="toc" class="toc" summary="Contents">
<tr>
<td>
